subject: August 2022 updates
message:
The patch this month brings in a number of sweeping changes for Fiery.  
 
&3&bNEW CLASS: BERSERKER!&0
&7&bBerserker is now officially enabled for play!&0
   - Allowable races are barbarian, dwarf, duergar, ogre, orc, and 
     troll.
   - Berserker is a subclass of warrior, following all the standard 
     subclass rules.
   - The subclass master is waiting up near the barbarian homelands in 
     the far north.
   - Berserker is intended as a high-damage, low-defense class.  The 
     signature characteristic, Rage, causes berserkers to become 
     aggressive to all targets, increases damage by 10%, but also 
     causes the character to take 10% more damage.
   - !Berserker has been added as a restriction on gear.  In general,  
     berserkers can use any weapon, but are restricted to light and  
     medium armor.
   - Berserkers have four guild halls throughout the world, and a 
     unique set of phase armor quests!
   - Berserkers also have access to the Chant skill for war chants and 
     other kinds of battle buffs, and the Meditation skill to help 
     them quickly regain their Rage.
 
From new !class flags, you'll also notice another class is in active 
development now too: &5&bBard&0.  We hope to release this class in the 
next few months.
 
 
&3&bRACIAL UPDATES&0
We made some racial balance tweaks to help each race be a little more 
unique.
 
&7&bTrolls and ogres had a difficult relationship for a long time.&0
   - Ogres were unparalleled in their front line combat capabilities 
     and vastly outshine trolls. Ogres have had their maximum hit 
     points and Constitution scores reduced, along with their AC 
     factor, while maintaining their Strength and damage roll 
     modifiers. 
   - Trolls have had their damage slightly reduced while pumping their 
     Constitution and hit point maximums much higher.  The goal is to 
     make trolls better damage sponges while allowing ogres to 
     continue to be brutal melee assailants.
   - Any troll player should see a god to have their HP readjusted.
 
&b&7Humans, half-elves, and orcs have received some stat changes.&0
   - Humans currently are the standard average, with no particular 
     drawbacks.  In order to give them something to stand out, humans 
     now have slightly higher stat caps across the board.
   - Due to centuries of learning to navigate two cultures, half-elves 
     have seen their Charisma cap increased.  They now stand out as 
     the most charismatic of the races.
   - Orcs have long been underpowered.  They've been the equivalent of 
     "evil humans" with less versatility.  Orcs now have some 
     variations in their stats.  They have had their Strength and  
     Constitution increased slightly, while having their Charisma 
     reduced.
   - They also now receive an innate to boost Strength called "chaz".
 
&7&bDwarves and duergar have had their innates changed and their class options broadened.&0
   - Dwarves and duergar have been accepted to the ranks of paladins 
     and anti-paladins respectively.
   - Their previous innate to increase Strength has been swapped out 
     for an innate that increases Wisdom, called "tass".
 
&7&bFinally, gnomes have had some significant changes.&0
   - First, a new innate skill has been created just for them: Create.  
     This skill mimics the spell Minor Creation.  It allows a gnome to 
     create the same list of items using the command:
 
     create <object>
 
     The skill has a cooldown of 75 seconds.
   - An innate called "brill" which boosts Intelligence has been added 
     for gnomes as well.
   - The Charisma cap for gnomes has been increased slightly.
   - The playable classes for gnomes have changed.  Gnomes can now be 
     druids, rogues, and thieves.  They may no longer become 
     diabolists because...
   - A new evil gnome race has emerged from the Underdark!  
     Sverfneblin, also known as deep gnome, is now a playable race!
   - Sverfneblins have the same stats as gnomes, and have access to 
     the brill innate.
   - They do not receive the Create skill.
   - Instead, they gain automatic Sneak in mountain, cave, and 
     underdark environments.
   - Sverfneblins may be the following classes: sorcerer, pyromancer, 
     cryomancer, necromancer, illusionist, cleric, diabolist, rogue, 
     thief, and assassin.
  
&7&bHalflings are still in the pipe for improvements.  New races are being developed now with the aim to release them soon.&0
 
 
&3&bNEW INNATES&0
New innate stat boosts have been created, one for each of the six 
stats. The Strength innate has been renamed, and the other five have 
been given unique names.
 
Charisma - Ascen*
Constitution - Tren*
Dexterity - Syll*
Intelligence - Brill
Strength - Chaz
Wisdom - Tass
(*currently unassigned to a race)
 
   - syntax: innate <name>
 
 
&3&bGEAR OVERHAUL&0
We have undertaken a total overhaul in the stats of weapons and armor.  
It may be the largest player-impacted change Fiery has gone through in a very long time.
 
There were many reasons this was badly needed:
 
&7&bItem strengths were outdated.&0
   - Most of the popular legacy items were built when Fiery stats were 
     on the 18-point scale, not the 100-point scale.  Some of the 
     items we remember fondly from the days of yore only added 1 or 2 
     points to a stat.  They simply weren't as effective when their 
     value was only 1/3 of their intended design.
   - Additionally, many characters start play with key stats of 90+, 
     meaning what had been intended to be the most valuable part of 
     most gear was functionally useless.
   - To address this, items have had their numbers changed across the 
     board.  Some have had their bonuses increased (from +1 to +3, for 
     example), while others have had the types of bonuses expanded 
     (adding additional +1 or +2 bonuses, instead of increasing the 
     original bonus).
 
&7&bFlavor text was often misleading and confusing.&0
   - There was a massive excess of level 1-10 gear with different 
     names/descriptions/flavor text but no functional difference in 
     stats.  New players were finding it prohibitively difficult to 
     understand why so many different items with identical 
     functionality exist.
   - A small handful of items, specifically level 1 daggers, have been 
     removed from the game and replaced with generic daggers.
   - Items with different descriptors now have distinct stats; "a 
     dagger" now has fully different stats from "a steel dagger", for 
     example.
 
&7&bItem levels and capabilities were extremely inconsistent.&0
   - Armor, weapons, and most jewelry now have levels in multiples of 
     5 so some of the guesswork about when an item becomes usable has 
     been simplified.
   - Many objects had vastly different levels but no difference in 
     functionality: a level 15 sword would often have the same stats 
     as a level 1 sword, for example.  It often felt unrewarding to 
     explore a new area and find nothing valuable for your gear setup.  
     It also meant certain pieces of gear were always the best, often 
     for 20-30 levels at a time.
   - Most gear now either reflects the levels of the zone it comes 
     from, both in level and in quality.
   - We've established a general progression for item values based on 
     the type of item, its composition, its level, and any additional 
     effects it might produce.  We used existing items as key points 
     to develop a smoother progression from level 1 to 95.  A higher 
     level item will always have better base qualities than a lower 
     level item of the same type.
   - All two-handed weapons now deal significantly more damage than 
     their one-handed counterparts.
   - Several zone "capstone" items have been massively improved.
 
&7&bMob compositions created a need for new types of damage.&0
   - Some weapons now deal fire, frost, or lightning damage.  NOTE: 
     These items CANNOT be used for specialized attacks like Backstab 
     or Throatcut.
   - These items are VERY FEW and far between.
   - Radiant damage weapons will be coming in the very near future.
 
&7&bGeneral bug fixes.&0
   - Some items have been fixed so they stop decomposing off their 
     wearers. The Creeping Doom quest should be unblocked with this 
     change.
 
 
&3&bNEW SPELLS&0
The Strength spell has been replaced with the more versatile Enhance 
Ability spell, which can be used to increase ANY of the six stats 
(Cha, Con, Dex, Int, Str, Wis).
 
   - syntax: cast 'enhance ability' <target> <stat>
 
 
&3&bSKILL CHANGES&0
&7&bGranted skill levels have been adjusted for many classes.&0
   - They now all unlock at a multiple of 5. Some skill levels have 
     been modified significantly. In particular, skill levels for all 
     rogue-types have been adjusted.
   - Rangers now get the rescue skill.
 
  
&3&bILLUSIONIST FIXES&0
   - Illusionists now get Mass Invisibility at Circle 8.
   - Additional fixes have been made to Simulacrum so your illusions 
     won't try to attack you anymore. (Note: they still deal damage 
     when they shouldn't. We'll fix that at a later date.)
 
-- Daedela~
~~
